<br>
What IS a 2D RPG?  Well, obviously, it's a 2D game, but aside from that, I feel it's more of a style.  When we think of 2D RPG, we think of sprites, little deformed people running around and such.  We think of the classic overhead view, watching from above, and we think of the graphics, most likely SNES style graphics.  All of this right here, that is the essence of the 2D RPG.  2D isn't just a dimension, it's a style, like I said before.<br>
<br>
Now, you must be thinking to yourselves "why don't you like 2D games?"  Well, now I'll start explaining.  The lack of realism.  I don't feel like the characters are in any way alive.  The are mindless drones that just say words.  Unlike books, which describe how people say things, or movies/TV, where you actually hear someone say the words, you have characters just reading lines.  Empty lines.  They don't have emotion, except for the occasional 'shocked' look or the laughing expression.  The characters don't have much to work with.  The sentance "Hey, that is neat." can be taken in many ways.  Someone could say it enthusiastically, sarcastically, somewhat bored, and so on.  When playing a 2D game, you don't know how that is said.  As for 3D games, that problem is approached differently.  For some mute games, like FF8, characters don't have voices either, or descriptions like in books.  What they do is body motions.  Someone will likely move their body in reaction to something being said, or while they say things, so you almost get the idea of how they feel.  Of course, FFX had the BEST characters, because they had voices.  You could tell their emotions from their voices.  AND FFX had facial expressions.  The characters moved and seemed like REAL people, adding to the games realism.  Overally, characters in 3D games seem much more realistic, and tend to resemble real people (with the exception of FF7, which was like a 2D game in 3D, a sort of mix in my opinion).<br>
<br>
Characters aren't everything though.  The storyline is important.  But with a good set of characters, who are developed nicely and all, the overall story comes off much better.  Not only, but for some reason, the plots in 2D games tend to be, well, cheesier than the more real looking 3D games.  I'll touch on that more later...<br>
<br>
I guess another thing that 3D obviously wins at is graphics.  A 3D game lets you see the world from MANY different viewpoints, rather than just from overhead.  I'm not going to argue about the quality of the graphics, that doesn't matter, but it does help enrich the environment.  That can be done very well in 2D games too.  I guess the only thing I really like is the fact that you don't have to see things at the same angle all the time.<br>
<br>
OK, now you're thinking, "HEY, graphics and all that flash aren't a big deal, the REAL content of a game is in the GAMEPLAY!!".  Yeah, this is true.  Also, in this aspect, 2D games could easily live up to and even surpass the gameplay than that of 3D games.  Notice how I said 'could'.  At this point, IMO, there aren't really many, if any, 2D rpgs that are actually better than say that of FF7, FFX, and so on.  I think that is just a sign of the times.  Since 2D is a thing of the past, and 3D is a thing of the present, it's obvious that the newer games present more quality than the older games, since they basically tend to ADVANCE in quality, not DEVANCE (that's probably not a word, but screw it, I'm making a point!)<br>
<br>
OK, so NOW you're thinking "Why don't they make an AWESOME new 2D RPG where the characters are really real looking, or maybe they have voice acting, and have great 2D graphics, with an incredible soundtrack, and a great gameplay.  That'll beat the pants off of 3D games!"  Well, in my opinion, why not just MAKE the game 3D?  If you're going to go all out like that, why not just take the next step?  Honestly, 2D is a thing of the past.  3D is in, and 3D games sell better.  People LIKE flash and great graphics.  I don't try to base my judgement on that, but many people do, and prefer games like that.  It just wouldn't be very economical for a company to do make a 2D RPG on PS2.  So where does that lead them?  Well, 2D still lives, and it lives on the Game Boy Advance.  BUT WAIT....  Who are the majority of people who own GBA?  Hmm, I'm going with a YOUNGER generation, like ages 6-12, and then some older gamers who have it for the sake of nostalgia.  Of course, these games are going to be aimed for younger gamers, making them easier.  AND, because 2D games have the natural tendency to come off as cartoony, they fit perfectly into the GBA theme.<br>
<br>
Now didn't I tell you I'd come back to why 2D plots aren't as great as 3D?  Well, if you haven't guessed it, then I'll tell you.  Since the 3D games attract more older gamers and mature gamers, and since they tend to be a bit more realistic, the plot of the game is more realistic.  2D games, which come off as a bit cartoony, and NOW only live on GBA (a predominently younger-generation system)  the storylines arent' going to be as good, or realistic.  We're going to see more corny storylines like in old FF games (where crystals were the balance of life, yadayada)  and all sorts of crazy crap.  In my opinion, 2D will eventually die off as more of a 'kid' thing, and eventually die off when 2D systems like GBA are gone.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, 3D is better.  My opinion was long, but this is the basis for my reasoning.<br>
<br>
